3.2.0 — Constitutional Purpose
This section defines the canonical data objects that form the structural fabric of the platform. Every feature, every flow, every interpretive output, and every ledger event refers to one or more of these objects. This section is binding.
All objects defined here are governed by:
•Section 3.0 — Governance Substrate (mutation guard, event ledger, operational modes)
•Section 3.4 — Causality Model (CCO binding)
•Section 3.5 — Trip Maturity States (lifecycle state machine)
•Section 8.4 — Permissioning & Audit Logs (role enforcement)
•Section 8.7 — Export & Data Egress Governance
•Section 9.4 — Interpretive Traceability
•Section 10.2 — Pricing & Entitlement Governance
•Section 15.0 — Stress Testing & Scenario Hardening

Invariants binding ALL objects in this section:
•No object may be mutated without calling precheck_mutation_guard()
•No object may be mutated without emitting a registered event via emit_event()
•All ledger writes are append-only. No UPDATE. No DELETE on event_ledger.
•Every object supports deterministic replay from the event ledger alone
•Soft-delete is permitted on domain objects; the deletion event is immutable
•GDPR erasure requests create a redaction event; they do not delete ledger rows

⚖ GDPR FLAG  GDPR Right-to-Erasure vs. Immutable Ledger: Section 8.x does not yet contain a formal erasure protocol. Placeholder classification is applied in Section 3.2.0.1 below. A dedicated erasure doctrine section must be written before commercial launch in any EU/EEA jurisdiction.

3.2.0.1 — GDPR Erasure Placeholder Doctrine (Pending Section 8.9)
Until Section 8.9 (Data Erasure & Right-to-Erasure Protocol) is written, the following placeholder rules apply to all objects in 3.2:
•PII fields are identified per object (see Compliance Sensitivity Classification in each object definition)
•Upon valid erasure request: a pii_erasure_requested event is emitted; affected fields are nullified in domain tables; the erasure_record_id is stored in metadata
•Event ledger rows are NEVER deleted. previous_state and resulting_state fields containing PII are redacted to "[ERASED]" strings in a separate erasure_redaction_log
•ITR records containing PII references are flagged pii_redacted = true; decision_fingerprint is preserved
•Erasure does not break ledger chain integrity. Checksums are computed post-redaction
