3.2.18 — Narrative Clarification Questions
The following questions require your guidance before certain behavioral logic can be finalized. They are written in narrative form to surface system intent, not technical details.

Q1 — The Incomplete Itinerary Trip
Walk me through what happens when a group organizer creates a trip with only a destination and departure date — no return date, no passenger list, no policy attached. The organizer saves and comes back two days later. Meanwhile, one participant tried to add their policy but couldn't find the trip to attach it to.
What should the system feel like at each of these moments? What is the organizer allowed to do with an incomplete itinerary? What is the participant's experience when they can't yet contribute? When does the trip move from DRAFT to PRE_TRIP_STRUCTURED — and who controls that gate?

Q2 — Late Evidence and Re-Evaluation
Imagine a user filed an incident and the system ran a benefit evaluation. The evaluation came back CONDITIONAL_ALIGNMENT because the airline confirmation email hadn't arrived yet. Three days later, the email arrives via the OAuth inbox importer and automatically attaches to the incident.
Should the benefit evaluation re-run automatically? Or should it go into a decision queue and wait for the traveler to explicitly request re-evaluation? Tell me the story of how that moment unfolds — from the email landing to whatever the user sees. Does the system feel proactive or controlled? Who decides?

Q3 — The Second Claim Against the Same Incident
A traveler files a credit card benefit claim for their trip delay. The claim status moves to submitted_by_traveler. Two weeks later, the card benefit is denied. Now they want to pursue the travel insurance claim for the same underlying disruption event.
Is this a second Claim object against the same Incident? Or does the platform expect this sequence from the start and model it as a routing sequence? Walk me through what happens — does the denial of Claim #1 automatically surface Claim #2 as a suggestion? Does it require a new routing recommendation? How does the evidence relationship work — is the same evidence packet used, or must the traveler rebuild it?

Q4 — The Protective Mode Scan
A major airline IT outage hits. The platform enters PROTECTIVE mode for the affected region. A traveler whose flight was just cancelled opens the app and tries to run a Deep Scan to understand their coverage.
Deep Scan creation is blocked in PROTECTIVE mode per the mutation guard matrix. But this traveler has a paid trip unlock and 2 remaining Deep Scan credits. From their perspective, they paid for this. They are in a stressful disruption moment. What do they see? What is the language? Is there a fallback — a cached result, a partial read-only output, a queue position? Walk me through what the system should communicate and what it actually does.

Q5 — The Archived Trip with a Pending Claim
A user has a trip in CLAIM_SUBMITTED state. They go back into the app and manually archive the trip — maybe they got frustrated and gave up. The Claim object is still pending an outcome.
Should the platform allow this? Should it warn? Should it block? If it blocks, what is the language? If it allows, what happens to the Claim — does it become abandoned automatically, or does it stay alive in limbo? Who can see a Claim for an archived trip? Tell me what the right behavior is and why.

Q6 — The Multi-Leg Trip and Incident Jurisdiction
A traveler is on a trip that passes through three countries — US departure, UK layover, France final destination. An incident happens in the UK during the layover. The trip's jurisdiction_ids includes all three countries. The policy has governing_jurisdiction pointing to US.
Which jurisdiction governs the incident? Is it the trip's jurisdiction set, or the incident's physical location, or the policy's governing jurisdiction? Walk me through what the platform should communicate to the traveler about this ambiguity — and how it affects what the Coverage Graph can deterministically say.


