3.2.33.A — Q1: The Incomplete Itinerary Trip
Q1 — The Incomplete Itinerary Trip
RESOLUTION: RESOLVED — Soft gate, organizer-controlled, participant-visible via search
 
Core Rule: DRAFT is a workspace, not a gate
An organizer creating a trip with only a destination and departure date — no return date, no passenger list, no policy — is in a legitimate planning state. The system does not block them, warn them, or apply urgency language. The trip remains in DRAFT state. DRAFT is not a problem; it is the starting condition.
 
The Organizer Experience
When the organizer saves an incomplete trip and returns two days later, they see exactly what they left: a draft workspace with a readiness indicator showing what is present and what is not. The system does not show a "you forgot X" warning. It shows a calm readiness summary: which segments exist, whether dates are set, whether a policy is attached. Tone is informational, never admonishing.
 
Approved copy: "Your trip is taking shape. Add your return date and route segments when you're ready — coverage analysis starts once your itinerary is confirmed."
 
PROHIBITED: "Your trip is incomplete." / "Missing required information." / "You haven't added X yet."
 
The Participant Experience
A participant who tries to find the trip to attach their policy cannot see a trip they have not been invited to. The trip is organizer-private in DRAFT state. The participant sees nothing — not an error, not a "this trip doesn't exist." The correct path is for the organizer to invite them.
 
This is not a gap. It is intended behavior. Participants do not browse-search trips. They join via invitation. If a participant says "I can't find the trip," the organizer needs to send the invite — the platform cannot and should not surface private draft trips to uninvited participants.
 
The DRAFT → PRE_TRIP_STRUCTURED Gate
The gate is organizer-controlled and explicit. The trip advances from DRAFT to PRE_TRIP_STRUCTURED when the organizer clicks "Confirm itinerary" — which is only enabled when: (a) at least one route segment exists, and (b) departure_date is set. Return date is recommended but not required at this gate. Passenger list is not required at this gate.
 
The system does not auto-advance the maturity state. Only the organizer's explicit confirm action triggers the transition. The confirm action emits trip_itinerary_confirmed, locks the itinerary_hash, and increments itinerary_version.
 
Behavioral Invariants — Q1
I-46	DRAFT state is never surfaced to the traveler as an error or warning state. It is a neutral working state.
I-47	Uninvited participants cannot see draft trips. The platform never surfaces trip existence to non-invited accounts.
I-48	The DRAFT → PRE_TRIP_STRUCTURED gate requires: (a) ≥1 route segment, (b) departure_date set. Organizer confirms explicitly. System never auto-advances.
I-49	Readiness indicators are informational (what is present) not prescriptive (what you must add). Language is never admonishing.
 


3.2.33.B — Q2: Late Evidence and Re-Evaluation
Q2 — Late Evidence and Re-Evaluation
RESOLUTION: RESOLVED — Proactive notification, traveler-controlled re-evaluation trigger
 
Core Rule: The platform is proactive in notifying, controlled in acting
When new evidence arrives via OAuth inbox importer — an airline confirmation email landing three days after an incident was filed — the platform notifies the traveler immediately and clearly. It does not silently re-run the benefit evaluation. It does not queue the re-evaluation for the traveler to discover later. It surfaces the new evidence and offers one clear action.
 
The platform detects. The traveler decides. The system never auto-re-evaluates coverage without explicit traveler confirmation.
 
The Exact Flow
• Evidence arrives via OAuth inbox importer → evidence_upload_completed event emitted
• evidence is causality_tagged to the open incident automatically
• The traveler receives a push notification: "New document arrived — your airline confirmation email has been added to your incident."
• The incident detail screen shows a banner: "New evidence added since your last evaluation. Want to re-run the analysis?"
• Traveler taps "Re-run analysis" → benefit evaluation re-executes → new ITR created → result displayed
• Traveler taps "Not now" → banner persists until dismissed or traveler re-runs
 
Approved copy: "New document added to your [Flight Delay — AC780] incident. Re-run your coverage analysis to include it."
 
PROHIBITED: Silent re-evaluation without notification. / Auto-updating the coverage result without traveler confirmation. / Losing the previous evaluation result.
 
Previous Evaluation Preservation
The prior benefit evaluation result is never overwritten. Each evaluation run creates a new InterpretiveTraceRecord. The incident detail screen shows the most recent evaluation prominently, with a "View history" option to see prior evaluations in chronological order. The traveler can compare what changed between evaluations.
 
Behavioral Invariants — Q2
I-50	New evidence attached to an incident triggers an immediate notification to the traveler. The notification names the document type and the incident.
I-51	Benefit evaluation never re-runs automatically. Traveler must explicitly trigger re-evaluation after reviewing new evidence.
I-52	All prior evaluation results are preserved as ITR records. No result is ever overwritten.
I-53	The re-evaluation banner persists on the incident screen until the traveler either re-runs or explicitly dismisses it.
 


3.2.33.C — Q3: The Second Claim Against the Same Incident
Q3 — The Second Claim Against the Same Incident
RESOLUTION: RESOLVED — Second Claim object, routing re-runs, evidence auto-shared
 
Core Rule: Multi-claim sequencing is modeled from the start
The claim routing engine (F-6.5.5) already generates a sequenced recommendation when an incident is first evaluated. It knows there may be multiple coverage paths. The routing recommendation includes sequencing: "File with Chase first. If denied, travel insurance is the next path." This is documented in the routing_recommendations table as sequence_position.
 
When Claim #1 is denied, Claim #2 is not a surprise to the system. The routing engine anticipated it. The platform surfaces it proactively.
 
What Happens When Claim #1 Is Denied
• Traveler records outcome on Claim #1: outcome = "denied", denial_reason_text provided
• claim_outcome_recorded event emitted
• System evaluates: does the routing recommendation have a sequence_position 2 path? If yes → surface it
• Banner appears on incident screen: "Your Chase benefit claim was denied. Based on your coverage, you may have a travel insurance path available."
• "View next step" → opens Claim #2 creation flow, pre-populated with incident data
• Claim #2 is a new Claim object against the same incident_id. It is not a continuation of Claim #1.
 
Evidence Relationship
Evidence is attached to the incident, not to any individual Claim object. When Claim #2 is created, all evidence already attached to the incident is automatically available to it. The traveler does not rebuild the evidence set. However, the denial reason from Claim #1 becomes new evidence — the traveler is prompted to upload the denial letter, which attaches to the incident as a new Evidence record of type "carrier_confirmation" with a note that it is a benefit denial.
 
The same evidence pool is shared across all Claims on an incident. Denial letters from prior claims are surfaced as actionable evidence for subsequent claims.
 
Does a New Routing Recommendation Generate?
Yes, but with the denial context loaded. The routing engine re-evaluates with: (a) the denial reason from Claim #1 as an input, (b) the denial letter as attached evidence, (c) the full original coverage graph snapshot. The new recommendation may differ in language and sequencing from the original. A new ITR is created. The old routing recommendation is marked superseded.
 
Behavioral Invariants — Q3
I-54	Evidence is incident-scoped, not claim-scoped. All claims against an incident share the same evidence pool.
I-55	When a claim is denied and a next-sequence path exists in the routing recommendation, the platform surfaces it proactively via a banner on the incident screen.
I-56	Claim #2 is a new Claim object with its own claim_id. It references the same incident_id. It is not a sub-record of Claim #1.
I-57	A denial letter from Claim #1 is treated as new evidence on the incident and surfaced as an input to the Claim #2 routing recommendation.
I-58	The routing engine re-runs for Claim #2 with denial context loaded. The prior routing recommendation is marked superseded, not deleted.
 


3.2.33.D — Q4: The Protective Mode Scan
Q4 — The Protective Mode Scan
RESOLUTION: RESOLVED — Cached result surfaced immediately, credits preserved, queue offered
 
Core Rule: Paid users are never left empty-handed
A traveler who paid for a trip unlock and has Deep Scan credits should never see a hard wall during a disruption. PROTECTIVE mode blocks new Deep Scan job creation — it does not destroy existing results. The platform surfaces whatever it has and tells the traveler honestly what it cannot do right now.
 
The Decision Tree
• Does a completed Deep Scan result exist for this trip's current itinerary_hash? → Surface it immediately with a timestamp and a calm note that this is a prior result.
• No prior result exists? → Surface Quick Scan coverage summary (cached or live, depending on mode) as a fallback, labeled "Coverage overview — Deep Scan unavailable right now."
• In both cases: show a queue option — "We'll run your full Deep Scan when service resumes. You'll be notified." Credits are NOT consumed until the scan actually runs.
 
Credits are never consumed for a blocked scan. The credit is consumed only when the Deep Scan job completes successfully.
 
What the Traveler Sees
Approved copy (when cached result exists): "Your Deep Scan from [date] is available below. We're temporarily limiting new scans due to high demand — your credits are safe and your scan will run automatically when things settle."
 
Approved copy (no cached result): "We're temporarily limiting new scans due to high demand. Your coverage overview is below. Your Deep Scan credits are safe — tap 'Queue Scan' and we'll run it automatically when things settle."
 
PROHIBITED: "Service unavailable." / "Try again later." / "Deep Scan is blocked." / Any language that implies the credit was spent or lost.
 
Behavioral Invariants — Q4
I-59	PROTECTIVE mode never consumes a Deep Scan credit. Credits are consumed only on successful job completion.
I-60	When a Deep Scan is blocked, any prior completed result for the same itinerary_hash is surfaced immediately with a clear timestamp.
I-61	A scan queue option is always offered when a Deep Scan is blocked. The queue promise is honored: the scan runs when PROTECTIVE mode lifts.
I-62	The traveler is never shown a bare error. Fallback content (cached result or Quick Scan summary) is always present when a Deep Scan is unavailable.
 


3.2.33.E — Q5: The Archived Trip with a Pending Claim
Q5 — The Archived Trip with a Pending Claim
RESOLUTION: RESOLVED — Warn and require explicit acknowledgment, Claim survives in accessible limbo
 
Core Rule: The platform warns, but does not block. The traveler decides.
A traveler who wants to archive a trip with a submitted claim has a valid reason to do so — they may be done with the platform's help, they may want to clean up their workspace, or they may have given up. The platform respects that decision. It does not block. It surfaces a calm, factual warning and requires explicit acknowledgment before proceeding.
 
The Warning Modal
Approved copy: "This trip has an active claim in progress. Archiving won't delete your claim or evidence — you can still access them from your claims history. Your claim will remain open until you record an outcome or mark it abandoned. Archive this trip?"
 
The modal has two buttons: "Archive trip" (proceeds) and "Keep active" (cancels). There is no third option. The traveler makes the choice explicitly.
 
What Happens to the Claim
The Claim object is not automatically abandoned when the trip is archived. It enters a claim_status of "submitted_by_traveler" (or whatever its current status is) and remains there. The trip's archived_at timestamp is set. The Claim continues to exist and is accessible via Claims History, not via the archived trip.
 
• Claims History is a platform-level view, not trip-scoped. It shows all claims regardless of trip archive status.
• The Founder can see all claims on archived trips via the FOCL claims view.
• Support can read but cannot mutate claims on archived trips.
• The traveler can record an outcome on the claim at any time, even after trip archival.
 
Behavioral Invariants — Q5
I-63	Archiving a trip with an active Claim is permitted. It is never silently blocked.
I-64	A warning modal is shown before archiving a trip with an active Claim. The warning is factual, not alarming. Explicit confirmation is required.
I-65	A Claim is never automatically abandoned on trip archival. The claim_status is not changed by the archive action.
I-66	Claims are accessible via Claims History regardless of their trip's archive status. Claims are never hidden.
 


3.2.33.F — Q6: The Multi-Leg Trip and Incident Jurisdiction
Q6 — Multi-Leg Trip and Incident Jurisdiction
RESOLUTION: RESOLVED — Physical location governs incident; policy jurisdiction governs benefit evaluation; both displayed transparently
 
Core Rule: Jurisdiction is layered, not singular
A trip passing through US, UK, and France — where an incident occurs in the UK, but the policy governs US — does not have a single governing jurisdiction. It has layers. The platform surfaces each layer transparently and does not resolve the ambiguity on behalf of the traveler. That is a legal question. The platform's role is to display all three layers clearly and flag where they conflict.
 
The Three Layers
• Physical incident jurisdiction: UK (where the disruption occurred). Governs statutory passenger rights — EU261 if UK has adopted equivalent post-Brexit, which it has via the retained EU law framework.
• Policy governing jurisdiction: US (as stated in governing_jurisdiction). Governs which law the insurer uses to interpret the policy.
• Trip jurisdiction set: US, UK, France (all three countries the trip passes through). Governs which regulatory overlays are shown.
 
What the Coverage Graph Does
The Coverage Graph uses physical incident location to determine which statutory rights apply. EU261 / UK261 equivalent is surfaced for the UK incident regardless of the traveler's nationality or the policy's governing jurisdiction. The policy benefit evaluation uses the policy's governing_jurisdiction for benefit clause interpretation.
 
Where these conflict — e.g., a US policy excludes something that UK statute requires the carrier to provide — the platform surfaces both and labels them clearly: "Your airline has a statutory obligation under UK aviation law" vs "Your insurance policy governs under US law." The traveler is shown both. The platform does not tell them which takes precedence.
 
The platform never resolves multi-jurisdiction conflicts with a single deterministic answer. It labels each layer, surfaces both, and directs the traveler to relevant authorities for legal questions.
 
Behavioral Invariants — Q6
I-67	Physical incident location governs statutory rights evaluation. The traveler's policy jurisdiction does not override statutory rights at the incident location.
I-68	Multi-jurisdiction conflicts are surfaced transparently with each layer labeled. The platform never collapses layers into a single verdict.
 


3.2.33.G — Q7: The Voice Narration Conflict
Q7 — The Voice Narration Conflict
RESOLUTION: RESOLVED — Proposal model, user chooses Replace or Add Both, no auto-deletion
 
Core Rule: Voice is a proposal, never an authority over confirmed data
This is already the platform's foundational voice doctrine (Section 7.4 and Section 5.0). When a user narrates "I want to fly Paris to Barcelona on June 10 instead of Prague," the system detects a conflict with a confirmed segment and never auto-resolves it. The narration creates a proposal, not a command.
 
The Conflict Detection Flow
• User narrates: "Paris to Barcelona June 10 instead of Prague"
• System parses: detects new segment (PAR→BCN, June 10) and a replacement intent ("instead of Prague")
• System finds the confirmed PAR→PRG segment
• Proposal screen appears with two clear options:
 
"Replace Prague with Barcelona"
Marks PAR→PRG segment as cancelled. Creates PAR→BCN segment. Itinerary version increments.	"Add Barcelona alongside Prague"
Creates PAR→BCN as an additional segment. Both segments remain. Route normalization flags the overlap as an UnresolvedItem.
 
• User chooses Replace → segment_status on PAR→PRG set to "cancelled" (not deleted). PAR→BCN created. Emits route_segment_cancelled and route_segment_added events.
• User chooses Add Both → both segments exist. Route normalization creates an UnresolvedItem: "Two segments depart from Paris on June 10 — which is your primary route?" The unresolved item blocks readiness confirmation until resolved.
• User taps "Start over" on the proposal screen → the entire narration is discarded. No segments are changed.
 
Cancelled Segments vs Deleted Segments
Cancelled segments are never deleted. They are marked segment_status = "cancelled" and remain in the data model for audit trail and potential reinstatement. The route editor shows cancelled segments as crossed-out with a "Restore" option. Deleted segments are not a concept in this system — the soft-cancel pattern applies always.
 


3.2.33.H — Q8: The Readiness Gate and Unresolved Items
Q8 — The Readiness Gate and Unresolved Items
RESOLUTION: RESOLVED — Two-tier: critical blockers vs advisory warnings. Traveler acknowledges warnings, cannot bypass blockers.
 
Core Rule: Unresolved items are tiered
Not all unresolved items are equal. The system distinguishes critical blockers (missing return date with flights booked past the departure date) from advisory warnings (connection buffer is tight but legally within airline operating minimums). The traveler can proceed through warnings with explicit acknowledgment. They cannot bypass blockers.
 
The Two Tiers
Tier	Examples	Traveler Action
BLOCKER — cannot proceed	Missing return date with booked outbound flight. Two segments with identical departure that cannot both be true. Invalid dates (return before departure).	Must resolve before "Confirm itinerary" is enabled.
WARNING — can proceed with acknowledgment	Connection buffer under 60 minutes (tight but within airline operating minimums). No return date (traveler may have one-way). Single segment with no policy attached.	Acknowledge warning → "Confirm anyway" becomes enabled.
 
Connection Buffer — Specifically
The connection buffer scenario from Q8 is a WARNING, not a BLOCKER. An airline may operate with a 45-minute minimum connection time. The platform flags it: "Your Paris → Prague connection is 48 minutes — this is within airline minimums but tight if your first flight is delayed." The traveler acknowledges and proceeds. The platform does not block them from confirming their own itinerary.
 


3.2.33.I — Q9: Activity Suggestion Rejection and Creator Discovery
Q9 — Activity Suggestion Rejection and Creator Discovery
RESOLUTION: RESOLVED — Independent systems. Rejection is session-scoped, not persistent. No cross-system suppression.
 
Core Rule: No creepy tracking. Two separate systems with separate data.
Activity suggestions in the Trip Draft engine (F-6.5.19) and Creator Discovery (F-6.6.11) are independent features with independent data models. A rejection in one system does not propagate to the other. This is intentional.
 
The Resolution
When a user rejects "Visit Senso-ji Temple" in their trip draft — because they've already been there — that rejection is stored on the ActivityCandidate record as decision = "rejected" with the reason captured if volunteered. It applies to the current draft session's activity suggestions only.
 
Creator Discovery is a separate browseable surface. A user searching "temples in Tokyo" sees Senso-ji in Creator Discovery because that feature does not read ActivityCandidate decisions. The user searching for temples may be researching for someone else, may have changed their mind, or may want to show it to a travel companion.
 
Activity rejection decisions are draft-scoped. They are never used to filter or suppress results in Creator Discovery, Search, or any other platform surface.
 
The line between helpful memory and unwanted tracking: the platform remembers what you've decided within a workflow (your trip draft). It does not build a profile of "places this user dislikes" that follows them across the platform. That is the line.
 


3.2.33.J — Q10: Group Trip Draft Collaboration
Q10 — Group Trip Draft Collaboration
RESOLUTION: RESOLVED — Suggestion queue for non-co-organizers. No real-time conflict resolution at MVP. Last-confirmed-wins for co-organizers.
 
Core Rule: Permissions govern contribution; proposal model governs conflicts
Group trip collaboration at MVP uses a two-tier model. Co-organizers can edit directly (with the standard proposal → confirm loop). Non-co-organizer participants submit suggestions that go into a queue for the organizer to approve or reject.
 
Bob Cannot Add a Segment Directly — Unless Made a Co-Organizer
If Alice has not granted Bob co-organizer status, Bob's attempt to add a segment goes into a suggestion queue. Bob sees: "Segment suggestion submitted — Alice will review." Alice sees a notification and an inbox item: "Bob suggested adding [segment]. Accept or decline?"
 
If Alice grants Bob co-organizer status, Bob can add segments directly with the same proposal → confirm loop as Alice. Both are subject to the same narration conflict detection.
 
Simultaneous Editing at MVP
Real-time conflict resolution is not implemented at MVP. Simultaneous editing uses last-confirmed-wins: whichever co-organizer confirms their edit most recently wins. The system does not merge or flag in-progress edits. If Alice and Bob both edit the same segment simultaneously, the last confirm wins and the other's edit is quietly superseded.
 
This is a known limitation for MVP. Phase 2 adds real-time conflict detection and a merge UI. The UnresolvedItems system handles post-facto conflicts that are detectable (two segments with identical departure slots).
 
MVP collaboration model: Suggestions for non-co-organizers. Last-confirmed-wins for co-organizers. Real-time conflict resolution is Phase 2.
 


